## 4. DTO Rules

- **Request DTO**: Input only; use for validation (`@Valid`), and use `@NotNull`, `@NotBlank`, etc. Do not expose entity or DB column layout.
- **Response DTO**: Output only; do not leak entity/table structure. Use clear, stable field names.
- **Dates**: Prefer `LocalDate` / `LocalDateTime`; avoid raw `String` or `Date` for API contracts when possible.
- **Codes / status**: Prefer enums over magic strings or integers in the API.

```java
// ✅ GOOD – request DTO with validation
@Getter
@Setter
public class ArtpromFileDeleteRequest {
    @NotBlank
    private String proId;
    @NotNull
    private Long fileId;
    @NotNull
    private Integer seq;
}
```

### 4.1 Jackson + Lombok: pXxx / cXxx field names (MUST)

**When you add or change a DTO that is (de)serialized by Jackson (e.g. `@RequestBody`, response body), you MUST handle the pXxx/cXxx naming exception.**

- **Why**: With Lombok `@Data`, a field like `pUserNm` gets getter `getPUserNm()` (capital P). Jackson infers the JSON property from the getter and can produce `"PUserNm"` instead of `"pUserNm"`, so request/response keys do not match and the value is null or missing.
- **Pattern to fix**: Any field whose name is **one lowercase letter followed by an uppercase letter** (e.g. `pUserNm`, `pEsntlId`, `pMbtlnum`, `pIhidnum`, `cIhidnum`). Normal names like `proId`, `userNm`, `reqEsntlId` are fine (multiple leading lowercase letters).
- **Action**: Add `@JsonProperty("&lt;exactFieldName&gt;")` on **every** such field in **both** request and response DTOs (so serialization and deserialization use the same key). Use the exact Java field name as the string (e.g. `@JsonProperty("pUserNm")`).

```java
// ✅ GOOD – explicit JSON key for pXxx/cXxx fields
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty;

@Data
public class ArtappmDTO {
    @JsonProperty("pEsntlId")
    private String pEsntlId;
    @JsonProperty("pUserNm")
    private String pUserNm;
    @JsonProperty("pMbtlnum")
    private String pMbtlnum;
    @JsonProperty("pIhidnum")
    private String pIhidnum;
    @JsonProperty("cIhidnum")
    private String cIhidnum;
}
```

```java
// ❌ BAD – no @JsonProperty; pUserNm may serialize as "PUserNm" or deserialize as null
@Data
public class SomeRequest {
    private String pUserNm;  // frontend sends "pUserNm" but backend can miss it
}
```

**Checklist when creating or editing a DTO used in REST (request or response):**  
Does it have any field named like `pXxx`, `cXxx` (single leading lowercase letter + uppercase)? → If yes, add `@JsonProperty("fieldName")` for each.

---

## 5. Service Rules

- **All business flow and decisions** happen in the Service layer (e.g. “delete file then clear parent’s file id if no files left”).
- **Transactions**: Use `@Transactional` at Service method level for operations that must be atomic.
- Controller only calls a single Service method (or a small, obvious set); it does not orchestrate multiple services or branches.

```java
// ✅ GOOD – business logic and transaction in Service
@Transactional
public void deleteFile(ArtpromFileDeleteRequest request) {
    fileManageService.delete(request.getFileId(), request.getSeq());
    if (fileManageService.isFileGroupEmpty(request.getFileId())) {
        artpromManageDAO.clearFileId(new ClearFileIdParam(request.getProId()));
    }
}
```

---

## 6. Repository / MyBatis Mapper Rules

- **Parameters**: Prefer a **single DTO or parameter object** per operation. Avoid `#{_parameter}` or unnamed primitives when a named DTO is clearer.
- **Updates**: Use explicit `SET col = NULL` (or appropriate value) rather than omitting columns; keep SQL readable and predictable.

### 6.1 Use DTO for parameterType and resultType (new mappers)

- **MUST**: For new mapper queries that feed REST APIs, use **DTO** for both `parameterType` and `resultType`. Do **not** use `egovMap` (or `resultType="egovMap"`) and then map rows to DTO in the Service layer.
- **Rationale**: MyBatis can map result set → DTO directly. Mapping in Service duplicates logic, hardcodes column names in Java, and mixes persistence mapping with business logic.
- **DAO**: Method should accept a request DTO and return `List<ResponseDto>` (or single `ResponseDto`). Service then validates, calls DAO, and returns; no row-by-row conversion.

```xml
<!-- ✅ GOOD – DTO in, DTO out; result columns in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (see §6.3) -->
<select id="selectDetailList" parameterType="DetailCodeListRequest" resultType="DetailCodeResponse">
    SELECT CODE_ID, CODE, CODE_NM, CODE_DC
    FROM LETTCCMMNDETAILCODE
    WHERE USE_AT = 'Y' AND CODE_ID = #{codeId}
    ORDER BY ORDER_BY
</select>
```

```xml
<!-- ❌ BAD – egovMap result forces Service to do manual EgovMap → DTO mapping -->
<select id="selectDetailList" parameterType="egovMap" resultType="egovMap">
    SELECT CODE_ID, CODE, CODE_NM, CODE_DC FROM ...
</select>
```

### 6.2 Type aliases (keep XML short and consistent)

- **MUST**: Register DTO packages (or classes) in **mapper-config.xml** under `<typeAliases>` (e.g. `<package name="arami.common.adminWeb.code.service.dto.request"/>`). In mapper XML use the **short alias** (class simple name), not the full qualified class name.
- **Rationale**: Keeps XML readable; aligns with existing Artprom/Artappm conventions; one place to update if package moves.

```xml
<!-- ✅ GOOD – alias from mapper-config.xml -->
<select id="selectDetailList" parameterType="DetailCodeListRequest" resultType="DetailCodeResponse">
```

```xml
<!-- ❌ BAD – full path in XML; use alias instead -->
<select id="selectDetailList" parameterType="arami.common.adminWeb.code.service.dto.request.DetailCodeListRequest"
        resultType="arami.common.adminWeb.code.service.dto.response.DetailCodeResponse">
```

### 6.3 Result column naming: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE in SQL (MUST)

**When you write or change MyBatis `<select>` result columns (including aliases), use the database naming convention: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.**

- **MUST**: Use **UPPER_SNAKE_CASE** for every result column/alias in mapper SQL (e.g. `USER_NM`, `ESNTL_ID`, `SCHOOL_NM`, `OFFM_TELNO`, `PROFILE_DESC`). Match the physical column name or a clear derivative (e.g. `SUB_NM_LIST` for a concatenated list).
- **Rationale**: This project has MyBatis `mapUnderscoreToCamelCase=true`. Result set names like `USER_NM` are automatically mapped to DTO properties like `userNm`. SQL stays aligned with the database; DTOs stay in Java camelCase; no duplicate naming in XML.
- **MUST NOT**: Do **not** use camelCase (or other non–database-style) aliases in SQL (e.g. `AS userNm`, `AS esntlId`). That breaks the single convention “SQL = DB style, DTO = Java style” and causes inconsistency and mistakes when copying from DB metadata or other queries.

**Prompt-style reminder for AI/developers:**  
“In waterb_backend MyBatis mappers, SELECT result columns and aliases MUST be UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g. USER_NM, ESNTL_ID). Do not alias to camelCase in SQL. DTOs remain camelCase; mapping is automatic.”

```xml
<!-- ✅ GOOD – result columns in database convention; mapUnderscoreToCamelCase maps to DTO -->
<select id="selectAcademyListForUserWeb" resultType="AcademyListForUserItem">
    SELECT COALESCE(A2.ESNTL_ID, '') AS ESNTL_ID
         , COALESCE(DECRYPT(A2.USER_NM), '') AS USER_NM
         , COALESCE(A2.SCHOOL_NM, '') AS SCHOOL_NM
         , COALESCE(A2.USER_PIC, '') AS USER_PIC
         , COALESCE(A2.PROFILE_DESC, '') AS PROFILE_DESC
      FROM ARMUSER A2
</select>
```

```xml
<!-- ❌ BAD – camelCase in SQL; do not do this -->
<select id="selectAcademyListForUserWeb" resultType="AcademyListForUserItem">
    SELECT COALESCE(A2.ESNTL_ID, '') AS esntlId
         , COALESCE(DECRYPT(A2.USER_NM), '') AS userNm
      FROM ARMUSER A2
</select>
```

**Checklist:** When adding or editing a `<select>` that returns a DTO: Are all result column names/aliases in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE? If you wrote `AS userNm` or similar, change to `AS USER_NM`.

